    "Smith, J. M. Powis (John Merlin, St. Jerome": "a hexameter + a pentameter, v. 'S' is a doublet of v.\n'\u00ab, (2)\na tetrameter + a hexameter, consisting of three dimeters (staccato movement).\nCf. V. '\u00bb,\njl3-lS\ng^\n13. Gird yourselves (with sackcloth,\ncf. v.\n*\u2022 ^^ Is.\n32\") and beat your breasts, O ye priests 1\nWail, ye ministers of the\naltar!\nCome (into the temple, cf. 2 S. 12^^), keep on your sackcloth\nday and night, ye ministers of God!\nThis accentuates the serious-\nness of the mourning and penitence.\nOnly in time of dire dis-\ntress and hard penance the sackcloth was kept on day and night,\ncf.\n13. See Vita Pauli 11; Contra Vig. 6; Ep. 127.14.",
